SigmaProverComputation
public class SigmaORTwoProverComputation
extends java.lang.Object
implements SigmaProverComputation

Concrete implementation of Sigma Protocol prover computation.

This protocol is used for a prover to convince a verifier that at least one of two statements is true, where each statement can be proven by an associated Sigma protocol. For more information see Protocol 6.4.1, page 159 of Hazay-Lindell.

The pseudo code of this protocol can be found in Protocol 1.15 of pseudo codes document at http://crypto.biu.ac.il/scapi/SDK_Pseudocode_SCAPI_V2.0.0.pdf.

Author:
Cryptography and Computer Security Research Group Department of Computer Science Bar-Ilan University (Moriya Farbstein)

computeFirstMsg

public SigmaProtocolMsg computeFirstMsg(SigmaProverInput in)
Computes the frist message of the protocol.

"SAMPLE a random challenge e1-b <- {0, 1}^t" for the simulator.

COMPUTE the first message ab in SigmaB, using (xb,w) as input.

RUN the simulator M for SigmaI on input (x1-b, e1-b) to obtain (a1-b, e1-b, z1-b).

The message is (a0,a1); e1-b,z1-b are stored for later".

Specified by:
computeFirstMsg in interface SigmaProverComputation
Parameters:
input - MUST be an instance of SigmaORTwoProverInput.
Returns:
SigmaORFirstMsg contains a0, a1.
Throws:
java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if input is not an instance of SigmaORTwoProverInput.

computeSecondMsg

public SigmaProtocolMsg computeSecondMsg(byte[] challenge)
                                  throws CheatAttemptException
Computes the second message of the protocol.

"SET eb = e XOR e1-b

COMPUTE the response zb to (ab, eb) in SigmaB using input (xb,w)

The message is e0,z0,e1,z1".

Specified by:

SigmaORTwoSecondMsg contains e0,z0,e1,z1.
Throws:
